                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1062">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Control Italy/8–944: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Mr.
                            <persName type="to">Robert D. Murphy</persName>, Political Adviser,
                        Allied Force Headquarters at Caserta</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-08-19T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 19, 1944—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>49. Department does not wish to pass on individual appointments to Italian
                    cabinet positions or diplomatic and consular posts. This Government is, of
                    course, interested in the elimination of Fascists from such positions and in the
                    appointment abroad of men who will cooperate wholeheartedly with their United
                    Nations colleagues. Names of appointees should, therefore, be reported to the
                    Department for its information but not for its advance approval in the absence
                    of exceptional circumstances.</p>
                <p>With the foregoing premise, the Department has no comment to make on the
                    appointments referred to in your 93, August 9,<note n="90" xml:id="d1062fn90"
                        >Not printed.</note> of Rossi Longhi and Gallarati Scotti.</p>
                <p>Repeat to Kirk.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
